<DOC><DOCNO> AP880704-0002 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 2344EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0681 07-04 0393</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0681,0397</SECOND><HEAD>Rain in the South, Heat in Michigan</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Louisiana rain, SouthDakota records. Picks up 7th graf pvs `Temperatures around...'</NOTE><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Storms soaked eastern Texas, Louisiana and Georgia on Monday,lightning blacked out a Colorado mountain city, and temperaturessoared in Michigan and South Dakota.   Rain showers and occasional thunderstorms reached from westernSouth Carolina and Georgia across eastern Texas and southeastOklahoma. Showers and thunderstorms also developed in the Dakotas,southern Montana, northern Wyoming and northwest Colorado, as wellas northwest New Mexico.   Lightning strikes caused a power outage affecting much of Craig,Colo.   In Monroe, La., 3.75 inches of rain fell between 5 and 7 p.m.The hard, dry ground didn't absorb the water, which rose fast andflooded streets. Several central Louisiana towns got an inch ormore of rain Monday night.   Thunderstorms produced 2\ inches of rain between North Houstonand Humble, Texas, and about 1{ inches in western and northwestHarris County, Texas.   Other heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 1{ inches at Macon, Ga., and almost one-half inch atMcAllen and Longview, Texas.   At least three Michigan cities reached high temperature recordsfor July 4 by early afternoon, with a record-tying 88 degrees inAlpena, and record-breaking 92 in Flint and 90 in Marquette.   South Dakota also sweltered through the holiday, with Rapid Cityand Aberdeen setting records for the date with 105 degrees.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 102 degrees at Yuma, Ariz. Thenation's low Monday morning was 38 degrees at Truckee, Calif.   The national weather forecast for Tuesday called for showers andthunderstorms from Florida across Alabama, southern Mississippi andLouisiana and from northern Montana across the northern PacificCoast.   High temperatures should be in the upper 80s and the 90s overthe Appalachians, the Great Lakes, the eastern Gulf, much of theOhio, Tennessee Mississippi and Missouri valleys, the Plains, thelower Rockies, Nevada and the southern Plateau. Highs in the 60sand 70s were forecast along much of the Pacific Coast. Temperaturesin the Southwest's deserts could reach 115 degrees. Hightemperatures over the rest of the nation were generally predictedto reach the 80s.</TEXT></DOC>